Sign-in worked but Save is still 403 — that rules out "cached old token". The brand-new token is being rejected by the API for one of the mutation-specific claims. I need to see what's actually in your token.

Use this snippet — it reads the token directly from IndexedDB (no SDK needed, so no `[DEFAULT]` app problem). Open DevTools → **Console** on `https://legacy-memories-prod.web.app/`, paste this, hit Enter:

```js
(async () => {
  const req = indexedDB.open('firebaseLocalStorageDb');
  const db = await new Promise((r, e) => { req.onsuccess = () => r(req.result); req.onerror = () => e(req.error); });
  const all = await new Promise((r, e) => {
    const g = db.transaction('firebaseLocalStorage', 'readonly').objectStore('firebaseLocalStorage').getAll();
    g.onsuccess = () => r(g.result); g.onerror = () => e(g.error);
  });
  const u = all.find(x => x.fbase_key && x.fbase_key.startsWith('firebase:authUser:'));
  if (!u) { console.log('No Firebase user found in IndexedDB'); return; }
  const t = u.value.stsTokenManager.accessToken;
  const payload = JSON.parse(atob(t.split('.')[1].replace(/-/g, '+').replace(/_/g, '/')));
  console.log('Decoded ID token payload:\n' + JSON.stringify(payload, null, 2));
})();
```

**Paste the output back here.** It will print a JSON object — I just need to see whether `practice_id`, `user_id`, `client_id`, `client_ids`, and `roles` are present (and what values they hold). The token doesn't contain anything secret beyond your identity, and only valid for ~1 hour, but if you'd rather, you can redact `aud`, `iss`, `iat`, `exp`, `auth_time`, `sub`, `user_id` (top-level Firebase one), `firebase`, and `email` — I only care about the custom claims I named above.

Once I see that output I can tell you **exactly** what's wrong in one more turn.

 The sign-in worked and gave us a fresh token, but Save is still throwing a 403, so it's not a stale token issue. Either the fresh token is missing the required claims or there's something else the API is rejecting. I should have the user export their token from the Network tab so I can decode it and see what's actually in there. Let me walk them through the DevTools steps to grab it.

Actually, I can make this easier by giving them a snippet that reads the Firebase token directly from IndexedDB where it's stored locally, then I can decode it myself to see what claims are present.

